article.description: Swin Cash scored 24 points and grabbed 14 rebounds to lead the Detroit Shock to a 68-57 victory over the Cleveland Rockers on Saturday night.
article.headline: Cash says Shock still having fun
article.linkText: Shock embrace spoiler status, defeat Rockers
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Swin Cash is having too much fun to worry about
her team's lost playoff status.

	   Cash scored 24 points and grabbed 14 rebounds to lead the
Detroit Shock to a 68-57 victory over the Cleveland Rockers on
Saturday night.

	   "We know we are a long shot to make the playoffs, but we come
out fighting every game,'' Cash said.

	   The Shock (7-20), who went on a 22-2 spurt against Cleveland,
were eliminated from a possible postseason berth earlier in the
week.

	   "Well, if we have to play the role of spoiler, we will do
that,'' Cash said. "We always play hard. We got on that run, and
points just sort of happened. That's what makes basketball so much
fun and why we all love to play it.''

	   Cash's double-double was her seventh in 14 games. The second
overall pick in this year's WNBA draft dominated with explosive
speed.

	   She scored nine points during the spurt that turned a 42-37
deficit into a 59-44 lead. The Shock snapped a two-game losing
streak and improved to 2-12 on the road.

	   The rookie forward credits coach Bill Laimbeer with not only her
development, but with the Shock's turnaround. Detroit is 7-10 since
the former NBA star took over an 0-10 squad in mid-June.

	   "The talent level has been the same all year, but he has helped
us really learn more about the game,'' Cash said. "He keeps our
spirits up.''

	   Chasity Melvin scored 15 points to lead Cleveland. Ann Wauters
scored 14, and Merlakia Jones had 13 for the Rockers (10-17), who
are 4-10 at home after going 14-2 at Gund Arena last year in
winning the Eastern Conference.

	   "We've had a lot of close games that we didn't quite finish
well,'' Rockers forward Mery Andrade said. "That's how the season
goes.''

	   Jones scored 10 points before being carried to the locker room
with a sprained left ankle with 17:44 to play and Cleveland ahead
37-36.

	   Cleveland held the Shock to just a free throw by Cash for the
first three minutes after Jones' injury. She returned two minutes
later with the Rockers ahead 42-38.

	   Then Cash took over, scoring on drives or connecting from the
free-throw line after racing past defenders and drawing a foul.

	   "She's really aggressive and we had a hard time trying to guard
her,'' Wauters said.

	   Deanna Nolan had five of her 16 points in Detroit's decisive
second-half run.

	   Cash, pushing the ball at every opportunity, sparked the Shock
to a 34-32 halftime lead. Detroit held an 11-2 advantage in
fastbreak points in the first half and finished with a 17-2 edge
overall.

	   Cash has averaged 19.3 points, 8.8 rebounds and 3.2 assists in
her last six games.

	   "She could go out and score more and take more shots, but she
doesn't because that is not her role,'' Laimbeer said. "She's by
far our best player. People are starting to realize what a mistake
it was not to have her on the All-Star team this year.''

	   Before the game, Detroit activated guard Edwina Brown and put
center Jill Chapman on the injured list with a strained lower back.

	   The Rockers played their second consecutive game without leading
scorer Penny Taylor (13.4 points a game). The second-year forward
is out because of back spasms.
